## Skeleton Loading Rule (AML)

Every view must show a **structural skeleton** that matches the final rendered layout during all loading states. Never use full-page spinners (e.g. `min-h-screen` + `Loader2`). This prevents Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS).

---

### 1. New page routes

Every new route group under `src/app/[orgSlug]/` MUST have a `loading.tsx` file that exports the matching skeleton as the default:

```tsx
// src/app/[orgSlug]/my-feature/loading.tsx
import { MyFeatureSkeleton } from "@/components/my-feature/MyFeatureView";

export default function Loading() {
  return <MyFeatureSkeleton />;
}
```

---

### 2. New view components

Every new view component that fetches data on mount MUST:

1. **Export a co-located skeleton** named `<ViewName>Skeleton` from the same file:

```tsx
// src/components/my-feature/MyFeatureView.tsx

export function MyFeatureSkeleton(): React.ReactElement {
  return (
    <ViewSkeleton hero={<PageHeroSkeleton showBackButton actionCount={2} />}>
      {/* Mirror the real layout with Skeleton elements */}
      <Card>
        <CardHeader><Skeleton className="h-6 w-48" /></CardHeader>
        <CardContent className="space-y-4">
          {[1, 2, 3].map((i) => (
            <Skeleton key={i} className="h-5 w-full" />
          ))}
        </CardContent>
      </Card>
    </ViewSkeleton>
  );
}

export function MyFeatureView() {
  const { isLoading } = useData();
  if (isLoading) return <MyFeatureSkeleton />;
  // ...
}
```

2. **Use `ViewSkeleton` from `@/components/skeletons`** as the outer wrapper to guarantee consistent spacing.

3. **Use `PageHeroSkeleton` from `@/components/skeletons`** whenever the real view uses `PageHero`.

---

### 3. View-skeletons map

Every new route MUST be added to `src/lib/view-skeletons.tsx` (`VIEW_SKELETON_MAP`). This map is consumed by `OrgBootstrapper` and the `[orgSlug]/layout.tsx` guards to show the correct skeleton while auth/subscription/settings are loading.

```tsx
// src/lib/view-skeletons.tsx
import { MyFeatureSkeleton } from "@/components/my-feature/MyFeatureView";

export const VIEW_SKELETON_MAP = {
  // ...existing entries...
  "/my-feature": ListViewSkeleton,          // list views
  "/my-feature/new": FormViewSkeleton,      // create forms
  "/my-feature/[id]": MyFeatureSkeleton,    // detail views
  "/my-feature/[id]/edit": FormViewSkeleton, // edit forms
};
```

Dynamic segments use bracket notation: `[id]`, `[importId]`, etc. The matcher handles any bracket pattern.

---

### 4. Generic skeleton reference

| View type | Skeleton to use |
|---|---|
| List + table | `ListViewSkeleton` from `@/lib/view-skeletons` |
| Create / edit form | `FormViewSkeleton` from `@/lib/view-skeletons` |
| Detail page | A co-located `*DetailsSkeleton` exported from the view file |
| Dashboard | `DashboardSkeleton` from `@/components/dashboard/DashboardView` |

---

### 5. What NOT to do

```tsx
// ❌ Full-page spinner — causes CLS
if (isLoading) {
  return (
    <div className="flex min-h-screen items-center justify-center">
      <Loader2 className="animate-spin" />
    </div>
  );
}

// ❌ Centered skeleton circles — not matching the real layout
if (isLoading) {
  return (
    <div className="flex min-h-screen items-center justify-center">
      <Skeleton className="h-12 w-12 rounded-full" />
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Route-aware structural skeleton
if (isLoading) return <MyFeatureSkeleton />;
```

Button/action spinners are OK — they don't cause CLS:
```tsx
// ✅ Action spinner (fine — doesn't shift layout)
<Button disabled={isSaving}>
  {isSaving && <Loader2 className="h-4 w-4 animate-spin mr-2" />}
  Guardar
</Button>
```

---

### 6. Responsiveness

Skeletons must be responsive using the same container query classes as the real components:
- Use `@md/main`, `@lg/main`, `@xl/main`, `@2xl/main` from `DashboardLayout`'s `@container/main`
- Grid columns should match the real layout: `grid-cols-1 @xl/main:grid-cols-2`
- Do NOT hardcode pixel widths for skeleton content — use responsive fractions or container queries
